IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: To enrich the character and leadership development of each person who has a Manito-wish experience, by challenging them to grow in wisdom, in stature, in favor with God, and in favor with one another. Since 1919, Camp Manito-wish YMCA has been helping youth build character, embrace traditional values and cultivate leadership skills. And while times may have changed, our methods haven't. We rely on our exceptional staff, spectacular northwoods setting, and dynamic, progressive program areas - Summer Camp, Outpost and Leadership - to challenge and inspire. Through these experiences, our youth discover new skills, talents and strengths. They gain fresh insights and understanding. And they see the world - and themselves - in a positive new way. Which just goes to show that while time moves on, and trends come and go, character and leadership never go out of style.
IRS990.MissionDesc: To enrich the character and leadership development of each person who has a Manito-wish experience, by challenging them to grow in wisdom, in stature, in favor with God, and in favor with one another.
IRS990.Desc: Summer Camp serves over 700 youth. The Manito-wish experience develops confident, responsible and enlightened leaders who will improve the world in which they live. Youth immerse themselves in activities designed to build character, shape leadership skills and inspire active involvement in our world. Financial assistance is available for participants.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Outpost programs serve over 200 teen age youth for extended camping experiences in the wilderness. Through our progressive wilderness tripping program, high school-age youth embark on outdoor adventures ranging from 9 to 45 days, backpacking, canoeing or sea kayaking to locations as beautiful as they are rugged. From the Apostle Islands to the Colorado Rockies to Alaska and the gates of the Arctic, Outpost campers encounter some of the world's most awesome environments that put their own abilities, character and leadership qualities to the test. Financial assistance is available for participants.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: Leadership programs serve over 2,000 participants through a diverse group of middle/high schools, youth serving agencies and colleges. Developing collaborative leadership skills, community awareness and fostering personal growth are keys to success in their experiences. Financial assistance is available for participants.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: All programs drive maintenance needs, additions and repairs along with safety and code guidelines.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 1a Delegate broad authority to a committee
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The corporation shall have an Executive Committee composed of at least seven (7) members and which shall include (a) the immediate past President of the Board of Directors, (b) the four (4) or more officers of the corporation (President, Vice President, Treasurer, and Secretary), the Chief Executive Officer and such other members of the Board of Directors to serve as at-large members as the President may from time to time appoint. The Executive Committee may exercise the powers of the Board of Directors with respect to the management of the affairs of the corporation when the Board of Directors is not meeting, except for: (a) electing officers or the filling of vacancies on the Board of Directors; (b) creating committees of the Board of Directors; (c) amending the corporation's Articles of Incorporation; (d) amending the corporation's Bylaws; (e) dissolving the corporation; (f) removing any member of the Board of Directors; (g) changing the Chief Executive Officer; or (h) authorizing or making any expenditures in excess of $10,000.00 unless previously included in a budget adopted by, or otherwise approved by, the Board of Directors.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 4 Significant changes to organizational documents
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Significant changes to the bylaws include replacing "Executive Director" with "Chief Executive Officer", replacing gender specific language with gender neutral language, the action without meeting section was modified to allow such action with the signature of 2/3 of the Directors then in office instead of all, a section was added about task forces, the non discrimination bylaw was updated, and amendments to the bylaws now require approval by 2/3 of the directors instead of a majority.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 15a Process to establish compensation of top management official
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Camp Manito-wish YMCA uses the Hay evaluation method to determine appropriate compensation for all positions, including CEO and top management. Annual evaluations are performed by the board president/executive committee for the CEO and by the CEO for top management staff.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Line 15b Process to establish compensation of other employees
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Camp Manito-wish YMCA uses the Hay evaluation method to determine appropriate compensation for all positions. Direct supervisors evaluate employees and all evaluations are reviewed by the CEO and HR prior to presentation to the respective staff member .
